                  "function_response": null,
                  "inline_data": null,
                  "text": "On the Bombardier Challenger 605, you can monitor the brake pressure and engage the parking brake by following the details below:\n\n### 1. Where to See Brake Pressure\nYou can view both the **Inboard and Outboard Brake Pressure** on the **HYDRAULIC Synoptic Page** of the EICAS (Engine Instrument and Crew Alerting System).\n*   **Reference:** Figure 15-10-8, *HYDRAULIC Synoptic Page (Inboard and Outboard Brake Pressure)*.\n*   **Location:** This is found in the **CL605-LANDING_GEAR** document on **page 15**.\n\n### 2. How to Turn on the Parking Brake\nTo apply the parking brake, follow these precise steps:\n1.  **Fully depress both brake pedals** on either the pilot’s or copilot’s side.\n2.  **Pull the PARKING BRAKE handle** (located in the cockpit, typically on the center pedestal).\n3.  **Rotate the handle 90°** to the locked position.\n\n**Confirmation:**\n*   When correctly engaged, a green **PARKING BRAKE ON** advisory message will appear on the EICAS.\n*   **Reference:** Figure 15-10-9, *Parking Brake*, and the \"Parking Brake Handle\" section in the **CL605-LANDING_GEAR** document, **page 15**.\n\n### Important Notes:\n*   **Pressure Requirements:** Both inboard and outboard brakes will hold as long as hydraulic systems 2 and 3 are pressurized. If the hydraulic systems are turned off, only the inboard brakes will hold for a prolonged period.\n*   **Low Pressure Warning:** If the pressure in either the inboard or outboard system drops below **1,015 psi**, an **INBD BRAKE PRESS** or **OUTBD BRAKE PRESS** caution message will be displayed (CL605-LANDING_GEAR, page 19).",
